{"id":"ev_c06ac462ba694d09","runId":"run_248","type":"delegation","at":1782487652688,"data":{"workItemId":"wi_834f04f332c64659","atom":0,"task":"Ticket 0064 — Atom 1 of a multi-atom fix: guarantee the Oz daemon ACTUALLY EXITS on shutdown/reload even when a dashboard SSE/keep-alive stream is still open. This is the root of the zombie bug.\n\nProblem (verified by Oscar): `packages/daemon/bin/oz.mjs` `shutdown()` calls `oz.close()`, and `OzServer.close()` in `packages/daemon/src/server.ts` (line ~238) does `server.close(() => { ctx.store.close(); resolve() })`. Node's `http.Server.close(cb)` only invokes its callback once ALL open connections have ended. The Electron dashboard holds an open SSE/event stream, so the callback never fires, `process.exit(0)` never runs, and the old process lingers forever as a zombie still bound to the dashboard. SIGTERM hits the very same wedged path, so it cannot kill it either (only SIGKILL did, in the incident).\n\nMake these changes:\n\n1. `packages/daemon/src/server.ts` — in the returned `close()`: after calling `server.close(resolveCallback)`, IMMEDIATELY force-terminate lingering sockets so the callback can fire. Node 18.2+/25 exposes `server.closeAllConnections()` — call it right after `server.close(...)` (guard with a `typeof` check for safety, but it exists on Node 25 which this runs on). This drains HTTP keep-alive AND the SSE/event streams. Keep the existing `ctx.store.close()` in the callback with its try/catch. The promise must now resolve promptly even with an open client connection.\n\n2. `packages/daemon/bin/oz.mjs` — harden `shutdown()`:\n   - Make it idempotent: a second SIGINT/SIGTERM while shutdown is already in flight must NOT start a second close (guard with a module-level `let shuttingDown = false`).\n   - Add a HARD force-exit watchdog: when shutdown begins, start a timer (e.g. 4000ms) that calls `process.exit(1)` unconditionally — the SIGKILL-self fallback the ticket requires, so the process can NEVER linger even if `oz.close()` hangs for any reason. Call `.unref()` on the timer so it does not by itself keep the event loop alive. Keep the existing `oz.close().finally(() => process.exit(0))` for the clean path; the watchdog only fires if the clean path didn't.\n\nAcceptance criteria:\n- A new/extended test in `packages/daemon/tests/` proves `createOzServer(...).close()` RESOLVES even when a client connection is still open against the server (open a real socket/HTTP request to the bound port that stays open, then assert `close()` resolves without hanging). Use an ephemeral port (`port: 0`) and the existing test injection options (inject `store`, `restartDaemon`, etc. as the other daemon tests do — look at `packages/daemon/tests/daemon-auto-reload.test.ts` and `read-surfaces.test.ts` for the established setup pattern, including injected `restartDaemon`/`buildDaemonForReload` no-ops so nothing shells out).\n- Do NOT change reload scheduling, the stale-detection logic, or `oz.sh` in this atom — those are later atoms. Touch only the close/exit path and its test.\n\nWrite-scope (do not touch anything else): `packages/daemon/src/server.ts`, `packages/daemon/bin/oz.mjs`, `packages/daemon/tests/**`.\n\nMust not break: existing daemon tests must stay green; the normal clean shutdown (no open streams) must still `process.exit(0)`.\n\nExit criterion (run these and paste output): `pnpm --filter @cocoder/daemon test` is green (including the new close-with-open-connection test) and `pnpm --filter @cocoder/core --filter @cocoder/daemon typecheck` passes."}}
